Cauley', u'\nVice President, General Counsel and Secretary', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Dated:\nSeptember 8, 2004', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'Table of Contents', u'\n', u' link1 "EXHIBIT INDEX" ', u'\n', u'\n', u'EXHIBIT INDEX\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'Exhibit\xa0No.', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Description', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'99.1', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\nPress Release Issued by Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. on\nSeptember\xa08, 2004', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'99.2', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\nText of Slide Presentation of Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. Used in\nConnection With the Company\x92s Second Quarter Fiscal Year 2004 Conference Call.', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'EX-99.1\n', u'2\n', u'k88056exv99w1.htm\n', u'PRESS RELEASE ON SEPTEMBER 8, 2004\n', u'\n', u'exv99w1', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'EXHIBIT 99.1', u'\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz Reports Second Quarter 2004 Results', u'\n', u'Northville, MI (September\xa08, 2004) \x97 Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. (NASDAQ:\nHAYZ) reported that sales for the fiscal second quarter, ended July\xa031, 2004,\nrose 4% to $523.7\xa0million compared with $502.8\xa0million a year earlier. Sales\nfor the six months ended July\xa031, 2004 were $1,117.8\xa0million compared to\n$1,018.1\xa0million a year earlier, an increase of 10%.\n\n', u'The Company reported a net loss of $10.0\xa0million, or 26 cents a share, for the\nsecond fiscal quarter ended July\xa031, 2004. For the fiscal first half of 2004,\nthe Company reported a net loss of $12.7\xa0million, or 34 cents a share.\n\n', u'For the second fiscal quarter of 2004, earnings from operations excluding fresh\nstart accounting adjustments and reorganization items was $9.5\xa0million,\ncompared with $20.4\xa0million a year earlier. Increased volumes and favorable\nexchange rates abroad were offset by lower OEM production requirements in North\nAmerica, lower unit pricing globally, and increased steel and iron prices. For\nthe six months ended July\xa031, 2004, earnings from operations with those\nexclusions amounted to $35.7\xa0million, compared with $34.8\xa0million a year\nearlier.\n\n', u'The Company reported a cash balance of $49.1\xa0million as of July\xa031, 2004 and\nthere were no borrowings under its $100\xa0million revolving credit facility.\n\n', u'\x93I am encouraged by our continuing progress in making Hayes Lemmerz more\ncost-efficient and customer-focused in our operations,\x94 said Curtis Clawson,\nChairman, President, and CEO. \x93Given the challenges faced by our industry,\nincluding sharply higher steel costs and soft new vehicle sales, we did well in\nthe second quarter. For the first half of 2004, we slightly increased earnings\nfrom operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and reorganization\nitems.\x94\n\n', u'Mr.\xa0Clawson cautioned that Hayes Lemmerz will continue to face high materials\ncosts, and also the impacts of new global competitors, especially in China.\n\x93Our industry remains under intense pricing pressure from competitors, and from\nour major customers. Fortunately, our intense focus on reduction in production\ncosts, facility improvements, and increased productivity is allowing us to\nrespond effectively to those pressures,\x94 Mr.\xa0Clawson said.\n\n', u'The 2004 fiscal second quarter results included $0.9\xa0million of restructuring\ncharges, primarily arising from severance and related closure costs of the\nHowell, Michigan, manufacturing plant as part of management\x92s ongoing\nrationalization efforts.\n\n', u'Results for the first half of 2004 also include a $12.2\xa0million loss on early\nextinguishment of debt. During the first quarter, Hayes Lemmerz sold 7.7\nmillion shares of its common stock in a primary offering, and used a portion of\nthe $117.0\xa0million net proceeds to extinguish $87.5\xa0million of its New Senior\nNotes and to prepay $16.0\xa0million of its New Term Loan.\n\n\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz will host a telephone conference call to discuss the Company\x92s\nfiscal year 2004 second quarter financial results today at 9:30 a.m. (ET). To\nparticipate by phone, please dial 10 minutes prior to the call: (800)\xa0399-3882\nfrom the United States and Canada (706)\xa0634-4552 from outside the United\nStates. Callers should ask to be connected to the Hayes Lemmerz earnings\nconference call, Conference ID#9644838. The conference call will be\naccompanied by a slide presentation, which can be accessed that morning through\nthe Company\x92s web site, in the Investor Kit presentations section at http://\nwww.hayes-lemmerz.com/investor_kit/html/presentations.html.\n\n', u'A replay of the call will be available from 12:00 Noon (ET), September\xa08, 2004\nuntil 11:59\xa0p.m. (ET), September\xa015, 2004, by calling (800)\xa0642-1687 (within\nthe United States and Canada) or (706)\xa0645-9291 (for international calls).\nPlease refer to Conference ID#9644838. An audio replay of the call is expected\nto be available on the Company\x92s website beginning 48 hours after completion of\nthe call.\n\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. is a leading global supplier of automotive\nand commercial highway wheels, brakes, powertrain, suspension, structural and\nother lightweight components. The Company has 43 facilities and one joint\nventure in 14 countries and approximately 11,000 employees worldwide.\n\n', u'More information about Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. is available at our\nwebsite which is www.hayes-lemmerz.com.\n\n', u'This press release includes forward looking statements within the meaning of\nSection\xa027A of the Securities Act of 1933 and Section\xa021E of the Securities\nExchange Act of 1934, as amended, which represent the Company\x92s expectations\nand beliefs concerning future events that involve risks and uncertainties which\ncould cause actual results to differ materially from those currently\nanticipated. All statements other than statements of historical facts included\nin this release are forward looking statements. Factors that could cause\nactual results to differ materially from those expressed or implied in such\nforward looking statements include the factors set forth in our periodic\nreports filed with the SEC. Consequently, all of the forward looking\nstatements made in this press release are qualified by these and other factors,\nrisks, and uncertainties.', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u' Begin Table Head ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u' End Table Head ', u'\n', u' Begin Table Body ', u'\n', u'\n', u'Press:', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'Marika P. 0002 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\nForward Looking Statement\n\nTHIS PRESENTATION CONTAINS FORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS WITHIN THE\nMEANING OF THE PRIVATE SECURITIES LITIGATION REFORM ACT OF 1995 WITH\nRESPECT TO THE FINANCIAL CONDITION, RESULTS OF OPERATIONS, AND BUSINESS\nOF THE COMPANY. THESE FORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS INVOLVE CERTAIN\nRISKS AND UNCERTAINTIES. NO ASSURANCE CAN BE GIVEN THAT ANY OF SUCH\nMATTERS WILL BE REALIZED. FACTORS THAT MAY CAUSE ACTUAL RESULTS TO\nDIFFER MATERIALLY FROM THOSE CONTEMPLATED BY SUCH FORWARD LOOKING\nSTATEMENTS INCLUDE, AMONG OTHERS, THE FOLLOWING POSSIBILITIES: (1)\nCOMPETITIVE PRESSURE IN THE COMPANY'S INDUSTRY INCREASES SIGNIFICANTLY;\n(2) GENERAL ECONOMIC CONDITIONS ARE LESS FAVORABLE THAN EXPECTED; (3)\nTHE COMPANY'S DEPENDENCE ON THE AUTOMOTIVE INDUSTRY (WHICH HAS\nHISTORICALLY BEEN CYCLICAL); (4) PRICING PRESSURE FROM AUTOMOTIVE\nINDUSTRY CUSTOMERS; (5) CHANGES IN THE FINANCIAL MARKETS AFFECTING THE\nCOMPANY'S FINANCIAL STRUCTURE AND THE COMPANY'S COST OF CAPITAL AND\nBORROWED MONEY; (6) THE UNCERTAINTIES INHERENT IN INTERNATIONAL\nOPERATIONS AND FOREIGN CURRENCY FLUCTUATIONS; AND (7) UNCERTAINTIES\nRELATED TO CONFLICT IN THE MIDDLE EAST. THE COMPANY HAS NO DUTY UNDER\nTHE PRIVATE SECURITIES LITIGATION REFORM ACT OF 1995 TO UPDATE THE\nFORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS IN THIS PRESENTATION AND THE COMPANY\nDOES NOT INTEND TO PROVIDE SUCH UPDATES.\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0003 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\n\n\n\n\nFinancial Statement Comments\n\nPeriod financial results are not comparable due to the\nCompany's emergence from Chapter 11\n\n\n\nEarnings from operations excluding fresh start\naccounting adjustments and reorganization items are\nused by management as the primary profitability\nmeasure (also referred to as earnings from operations\nexcluding one-time adjustments in this presentation)\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0004 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nAgenda\n\nCompany Highlights\n\n   Curt Clawson, President, CEO & Chairman of the Board\n\n\n\nFinancial Review\n\n   Jim Yost, Vice President of Finance & CFO\n\n\n\n2004 Outlook\n\n   Jim Yost, Vice President of Finance & CFO\n\n\n\nQ&A\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0005 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nGrow by satisfying customers\n\nBe the lowest cost producer\n\nHave the best people in the industry\n\nOur Vision\n\nPremier Automotive Supplier\n\nCONTINUED PROGRESS IN ALL THREE AREAS\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0006 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nCompany Highlights\n\nContinued sales growth\n\nFavorable currency and acquisitions added to top line.  GAAP\n\nFinancial Measures\n\nEarnings (from operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and\nreorganization items:\n\nEarnings from operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and\nreorganization items is used by management as a non-GAAP financial measure of the\nCompany's primary profitability measure because it excludes fresh start accounting\nadjustments and reorganization items which do not represent normal operating\nperformance of the Company as these items relate only to the Company's Chapter 11\nfilings and emergence.\n\n\n\nFree Cash Flow:\n\n Free cash flow is used by management as a non-GAAP financial measure because it\nidentifies the amount of cash available to meet principal debt amortization requirements,\npay dividends to stockholders, or make corporate investments.\n\n\n\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0025 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\nFinancial Measures\n\n\n\nAdjusted EBITDA:\n\n EBITDA, a measure used by management to measure operating performance, is defined\nas earnings from operations plus depreciation and amortization. Adjusted EBITDA is\ndefined as EBITDA further adjusted to exclude: (i) asset impairment losses and other\nrestructuring charges; (ii) reorganization items; and (iii) other items. We reference these\nnon-GAAP financial measures as a management group frequently in our decision making\nbecause they provide supplemental information that facilitates internal comparisons to\nhistorical operating performance of prior periods and external comparisons to competitors'\nhistorical operating performance. Institutional investors generally look to Adjusted EBITDA\nin measuring performance, among other things. We use Adjusted EBITDA to facilitate\nquantification of planned business activities and enhance subsequent follow-up with\ncomparisons of actual to planned Adjusted EBITDA. In addition, incentive compensation\nfor management is based on Adjusted EBITDA. We are disclosing these non-GAAP\nfinancial measures in order to provide transparency to investors.\n\n     Adjusted EBITDA is not a recognized term under GAAP and does not purport to be an\nalternative to earnings from operations as an indicator of operating performance or to\ncash flows from operating activities as a measure of liquidity. Because not all companies\nuse identical calculations, these presentations of Adjusted EBITDA may not be\ncomparable to other similarly titled measures of other companies. Additionally, Adjusted\nEBITDA is not intended to be a measure of free cash flow for management's discretionary\nuse, as it does not consider certain cash requirements such as interest payments, tax\npayments and debt service requirements.\n", u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'GRAPHIC\n', u'4\n', u'k88056k880561z0001.gif\n', u'GRAPHIC\n', u'\nbegin 644 Cauley', u'\nVice President, General Counsel and Secretary', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Dated:\nSeptember 8, 2004', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'Table of Contents', u'\n', u' link1 "EXHIBIT INDEX" ', u'\n', u'\n', u'EXHIBIT INDEX\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'Exhibit\xa0No.', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Description', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'99.1', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\nPress Release Issued by Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. on\nSeptember\xa08, 2004', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'99.2', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\nText of Slide Presentation of Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. Used in\nConnection With the Company\x92s Second Quarter Fiscal Year 2004 Conference Call.', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'EX-99.1\n', u'2\n', u'k88056exv99w1.htm\n', u'PRESS RELEASE ON SEPTEMBER 8, 2004\n', u'\n', u'exv99w1', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'EXHIBIT 99.1', u'\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz Reports Second Quarter 2004 Results', u'\n', u'Northville, MI (September\xa08, 2004) \x97 Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. (NASDAQ:\nHAYZ) reported that sales for the fiscal second quarter, ended July\xa031, 2004,\nrose 4% to $523.7\xa0million compared with $502.8\xa0million a year earlier. Sales\nfor the six months ended July\xa031, 2004 were $1,117.8\xa0million compared to\n$1,018.1\xa0million a year earlier, an increase of 10%.\n\n', u'The Company reported a net loss of $10.0\xa0million, or 26 cents a share, for the\nsecond fiscal quarter ended July\xa031, 2004. For the fiscal first half of 2004,\nthe Company reported a net loss of $12.7\xa0million, or 34 cents a share.\n\n', u'For the second fiscal quarter of 2004, earnings from operations excluding fresh\nstart accounting adjustments and reorganization items was $9.5\xa0million,\ncompared with $20.4\xa0million a year earlier. Increased volumes and favorable\nexchange rates abroad were offset by lower OEM production requirements in North\nAmerica, lower unit pricing globally, and increased steel and iron prices. For\nthe six months ended July\xa031, 2004, earnings from operations with those\nexclusions amounted to $35.7\xa0million, compared with $34.8\xa0million a year\nearlier.\n\n', u'The Company reported a cash balance of $49.1\xa0million as of July\xa031, 2004 and\nthere were no borrowings under its $100\xa0million revolving credit facility.\n\n', u'\x93I am encouraged by our continuing progress in making Hayes Lemmerz more\ncost-efficient and customer-focused in our operations,\x94 said Curtis Clawson,\nChairman, President, and CEO. \x93Given the challenges faced by our industry,\nincluding sharply higher steel costs and soft new vehicle sales, we did well in\nthe second quarter. For the first half of 2004, we slightly increased earnings\nfrom operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and reorganization\nitems.\x94\n\n', u'Mr.\xa0Clawson cautioned that Hayes Lemmerz will continue to face high materials\ncosts, and also the impacts of new global competitors, especially in China.\n\x93Our industry remains under intense pricing pressure from competitors, and from\nour major customers. Fortunately, our intense focus on reduction in production\ncosts, facility improvements, and increased productivity is allowing us to\nrespond effectively to those pressures,\x94 Mr.\xa0Clawson said.\n\n', u'The 2004 fiscal second quarter results included $0.9\xa0million of restructuring\ncharges, primarily arising from severance and related closure costs of the\nHowell, Michigan, manufacturing plant as part of management\x92s ongoing\nrationalization efforts.\n\n', u'Results for the first half of 2004 also include a $12.2\xa0million loss on early\nextinguishment of debt. During the first quarter, Hayes Lemmerz sold 7.7\nmillion shares of its common stock in a primary offering, and used a portion of\nthe $117.0\xa0million net proceeds to extinguish $87.5\xa0million of its New Senior\nNotes and to prepay $16.0\xa0million of its New Term Loan.\n\n\n', u'\xa0\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u'\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz will host a telephone conference call to discuss the Company\x92s\nfiscal year 2004 second quarter financial results today at 9:30 a.m. (ET). To\nparticipate by phone, please dial 10 minutes prior to the call: (800)\xa0399-3882\nfrom the United States and Canada (706)\xa0634-4552 from outside the United\nStates. Callers should ask to be connected to the Hayes Lemmerz earnings\nconference call, Conference ID#9644838. The conference call will be\naccompanied by a slide presentation, which can be accessed that morning through\nthe Company\x92s web site, in the Investor Kit presentations section at http://\nwww.hayes-lemmerz.com/investor_kit/html/presentations.html.\n\n', u'A replay of the call will be available from 12:00 Noon (ET), September\xa08, 2004\nuntil 11:59\xa0p.m. (ET), September\xa015, 2004, by calling (800)\xa0642-1687 (within\nthe United States and Canada) or (706)\xa0645-9291 (for international calls).\nPlease refer to Conference ID#9644838. An audio replay of the call is expected\nto be available on the Company\x92s website beginning 48 hours after completion of\nthe call.\n\n', u'Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. is a leading global supplier of automotive\nand commercial highway wheels, brakes, powertrain, suspension, structural and\nother lightweight components. The Company has 43 facilities and one joint\nventure in 14 countries and approximately 11,000 employees worldwide.\n\n', u'More information about Hayes Lemmerz International, Inc. is available at our\nwebsite which is www.hayes-lemmerz.com.\n\n', u'This press release includes forward looking statements within the meaning of\nSection\xa027A of the Securities Act of 1933 and Section\xa021E of the Securities\nExchange Act of 1934, as amended, which represent the Company\x92s expectations\nand beliefs concerning future events that involve risks and uncertainties which\ncould cause actual results to differ materially from those currently\nanticipated. 0002 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\nForward Looking Statement\n\nTHIS PRESENTATION CONTAINS FORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS WITHIN THE\nMEANING OF THE PRIVATE SECURITIES LITIGATION REFORM ACT OF 1995 WITH\nRESPECT TO THE FINANCIAL CONDITION, RESULTS OF OPERATIONS, AND BUSINESS\nOF THE COMPANY. THESE FORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS INVOLVE CERTAIN\nRISKS AND UNCERTAINTIES. NO ASSURANCE CAN BE GIVEN THAT ANY OF SUCH\nMATTERS WILL BE REALIZED. FACTORS THAT MAY CAUSE ACTUAL RESULTS TO\nDIFFER MATERIALLY FROM THOSE CONTEMPLATED BY SUCH FORWARD LOOKING\nSTATEMENTS INCLUDE, AMONG OTHERS, THE FOLLOWING POSSIBILITIES: (1)\nCOMPETITIVE PRESSURE IN THE COMPANY'S INDUSTRY INCREASES SIGNIFICANTLY;\n(2) GENERAL ECONOMIC CONDITIONS ARE LESS FAVORABLE THAN EXPECTED; (3)\nTHE COMPANY'S DEPENDENCE ON THE AUTOMOTIVE INDUSTRY (WHICH HAS\nHISTORICALLY BEEN CYCLICAL); (4) PRICING PRESSURE FROM AUTOMOTIVE\nINDUSTRY CUSTOMERS; (5) CHANGES IN THE FINANCIAL MARKETS AFFECTING THE\nCOMPANY'S FINANCIAL STRUCTURE AND THE COMPANY'S COST OF CAPITAL AND\nBORROWED MONEY; (6) THE UNCERTAINTIES INHERENT IN INTERNATIONAL\nOPERATIONS AND FOREIGN CURRENCY FLUCTUATIONS; AND (7) UNCERTAINTIES\nRELATED TO CONFLICT IN THE MIDDLE EAST. THE COMPANY HAS NO DUTY UNDER\nTHE PRIVATE SECURITIES LITIGATION REFORM ACT OF 1995 TO UPDATE THE\nFORWARD LOOKING STATEMENTS IN THIS PRESENTATION AND THE COMPANY\nDOES NOT INTEND TO PROVIDE SUCH UPDATES.\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0003 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\n\n\n\n\nFinancial Statement Comments\n\nPeriod financial results are not comparable due to the\nCompany's emergence from Chapter 11\n\n\n\nEarnings from operations excluding fresh start\naccounting adjustments and reorganization items are\nused by management as the primary profitability\nmeasure (also referred to as earnings from operations\nexcluding one-time adjustments in this presentation)\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0004 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nAgenda\n\nCompany Highlights\n\n   Curt Clawson, President, CEO & Chairman of the Board\n\n\n\nFinancial Review\n\n   Jim Yost, Vice President of Finance & CFO\n\n\n\n2004 Outlook\n\n   Jim Yost, Vice President of Finance & CFO\n\n\n\nQ&A\n\n\n\n\n\n\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0005 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nGrow by satisfying customers\n\nBe the lowest cost producer\n\nHave the best people in the industry\n\nOur Vision\n\nPremier Automotive Supplier\n\nCONTINUED PROGRESS IN ALL THREE AREAS\n', u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0006 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n\nCompany Highlights\n\nContinued sales growth\n\nFavorable currency and acquisitions added to top line.  GAAP\n\nFinancial Measures\n\nEarnings (from operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and\nreorganization items:\n\nEarnings from operations excluding fresh start accounting adjustments and\nreorganization items is used by management as a non-GAAP financial measure of the\nCompany's primary profitability measure because it excludes fresh start accounting\nadjustments and reorganization items which do not represent normal operating\nperformance of the Company as these items relate only to the Company's Chapter 11\nfilings and emergence.\n\n\n\nFree Cash Flow:\n\n Free cash flow is used by management as a non-GAAP financial measure because it\nidentifies the amount of cash available to meet principal debt amortization requirements,\npay dividends to stockholders, or make corporate investments.\n\n\n\n", u'\n', u' PAGEBREAK ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\xa0', u'\n', u' Slide Number 0025 ', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u'\n', u"\n\nFinancial Measures\n\n\n\nAdjusted EBITDA:\n\n EBITDA, a measure used by management to measure operating performance, is defined\nas earnings from operations plus depreciation and amortization. Adjusted EBITDA is\ndefined as EBITDA further adjusted to exclude: (i) asset impairment losses and other\nrestructuring charges; (ii) reorganization items; and (iii) other items. We reference these\nnon-GAAP financial measures as a management group frequently in our decision making\nbecause they provide supplemental information that facilitates internal comparisons to\nhistorical operating performance of prior periods and external comparisons to competitors'\nhistorical operating performance. Institutional investors generally look to Adjusted EBITDA\nin measuring performance, among other things. We use Adjusted EBITDA to facilitate\nquantification of planned business activities and enhance subsequent follow-up with\ncomparisons of actual to planned Adjusted EBITDA. In addition, incentive compensation\nfor management is based on Adjusted EBITDA. We are disclosing these non-GAAP\nfinancial measures in order to provide transparency to investors.\n\n     Adjusted EBITDA is not a recognized term under GAAP and does not purport to be an\nalternative to earnings from operations as an indicator of operating performance or to\ncash flows from operating activities as a measure of liquidity. Because not all companies\nuse identical calculations, these presentations of Adjusted EBITDA may not be\ncomparable to other similarly titled measures of other companies. Additionally, Adjusted\nEBITDA is not intended to be a measure of free cash flow for management's discretionary\nuse, as it does not consider certain cash requirements such as interest payments,
